\begin_layout Section
2011-07-14: Attempt #3: PAF-Gold Chloride Protocol (Khanna, 1986)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 1986, Khanna et al.
 published a protocol for the fabrication of gold mirrors for use in interferome
try based upon the techniques by Chiang and Turkevich in 1963.
 The target dimension was a diameter of 50 to 100 microns, with the gold
 mirrors being flat hexagonal plates.
 The group added 1 g gold chloride to 119 ml deionized water.
 After filtering and bringing the pH to 1.1 through the addition of 8.73 ml
 of 20% EtOH, formalin was added to the solution.
 A concentration of formalin was not noted in the protocol.
 The solution was then incubated at 91-92C for 2 hours and subsequently
 transferred to an evaporation dish in a 37C water bath.
 This was left undisturbed for 4 to 5 weeks to allow the crystals to grow.
 The group estimated the gold mirrors to have a diameter of 4E-8 to 7E-9
 g at a 75 micron diameter.
 However, the most successful attempts yielded a low number of optically
 active gold disks of the correct dimension and shape.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This protocol will adapt the protocol by Khanna in a smaller volume and
 using the materials currently available.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Day 0 - 
\series default
